      "hadean": "Hadean",
      "the_hadean_eon_4_6_4_0_ga_earth_formed": "The Hadean Eon (4.6-4.0 Ga). Earth formed from solar nebula accretion. The surface was a magma ocean bombarded by meteorites. The Moon formed from a giant impact. No tectonic plates existed.",
      "archean": "Archean",
      "the_archean_eon_4_0_2_5_ga_earth_s_cru": "The Archean Eon (4.0-2.5 Ga). Earth's crust solidified. Small protocontinents called cratons formed the first stable landmasses. Plate tectonics may have begun. Oceans covered most of the surface.",
      "rodinia": "Rodinia",
      "the_mesoproterozoic_era_rodinia_was_ea": "The Mesoproterozoic Era. Rodinia was Earth's first supercontinent, assembling ~1.1 Ga. All major cratons were joined. Its breakup (~750 Ma) triggered Snowball Earth glaciations and eventually led to the Cambrian explosion of life.",
      "pangaea": "Pangaea",
      "the_late_paleozoic_carboniferous_permi": "The late Paleozoic (Carboniferous-Permian). Pangaea (\"All Earth\") was the most recent supercontinent. It stretched from pole to pole. The Tethys Sea separated its eastern margins. Coal swamps covered equatorial regions.",
      "breakup": "Breakup",
      "the_triassic_jurassic_boundary_pangaea": "The Triassic-Jurassic boundary. Pangaea began rifting ~200 Ma. The central Atlantic opened as North America separated from Africa. Dinosaurs dominated both halves. Laurasia = N. America + Eurasia. Gondwana = S. America + Africa + India + Antarctica + Australia.",
      "cretaceous": "Cretaceous",
      "the_cretaceous_period_south_america_se": "The Cretaceous Period. South America separated from Africa. India detached from Antarctica and began its northward journey at ~15 cm/year. The Atlantic Ocean widened significantly. Sea levels were 200m higher than today. Dinosaurs still ruled.",
      "cenozoic": "Cenozoic",
      "the_early_cenozoic_eocene_india_s_coll": "The early Cenozoic (Eocene). India's collision with Eurasia created the Himalayas and Tibetan Plateau. Australia separated from Antarctica. The Alps formed as Africa pushed into Europe. Mammals diversified after the dinosaur extinction.",
      "modern": "Modern",
      "the_present_day_seven_major_tectonic_p": "The present day. Seven major tectonic plates move at 2-10 cm/year. The Atlantic continues to widen. The Pacific Ring of Fire hosts 75% of the world's volcanoes. The Himalayas still rise ~5mm/year as India pushes into Eurasia.",
      "plate_tectonics_keyboard_shortcuts_1_t": "Plate Tectonics. Keyboard shortcuts: 1 through 4 switch tabs, L toggles labels, C toggles convection currents.",
