      "plafker_confirmed_subduction_mechanism": "Plafker confirmed subduction mechanism.",
      "quick_review_questions": "Quick-Review Questions",
      "60_quick_review_questions_covering_key": "60 quick review questions covering key plate tectonic concepts. Use as flash cards: read the question, try to answer in your head, then check below.",
      "review_question_1": "Review question 1",
      "concept_plate_boundaries": "Concept: plate boundaries",
      "question_what_is_a_divergent_boundary": "Question: What is a divergent boundary?",
      "answer_a_divergent_plate_boundary_is_w": "Answer: A divergent plate boundary is where two plates are moving away from each other, often forming a mid-ocean ridge or continental rift. Examples include the Mid-Atlantic Ridge and the East African Rift.",
      "review_question_2": "Review question 2",
      "concept_earthquake_magnitude": "Concept: earthquake magnitude",
      "question_what_is_the_richter_scale": "Question: What is the Richter scale?",
      "answer_the_richter_scale_was_the_origi": "Answer: The Richter scale was the original 1935 magnitude scale developed by Charles Richter. It is logarithmic, so M5 is 10x larger than M4. It works well for small to medium quakes but saturates above M7. Modern seismology uses moment magnitude (Mw) for large events.",
      "review_question_3": "Review question 3",
      "concept_volcanic_types": "Concept: volcanic types",
      "question_what_is_a_stratovolcano": "Question: What is a stratovolcano?",
      "answer_a_stratovolcano_is_a_steep_side": "Answer: A stratovolcano is a steep-sided conical volcano built from alternating layers of lava and ash. Examples include Mt Fuji, Mt St Helens, and Vesuvius. They tend to produce explosive eruptions.",
      "review_question_4": "Review question 4",
      "concept_rock_cycle": "Concept: rock cycle",
      "question_what_is_metamorphic_rock_form": "Question: What is metamorphic rock formation?",
      "answer_metamorphic_rocks_form_when_exi": "Answer: Metamorphic rocks form when existing rocks are transformed by heat, pressure, or chemically active fluids. Examples include marble (from limestone), slate (from shale), and gneiss (from granite).",
      "review_question_5": "Review question 5",
      "concept_geological_time": "Concept: geological time",
      "question_what_is_the_cenozoic_era": "Question: What is the Cenozoic Era?",
      "answer_the_cenozoic_era_began_66_milli": "Answer: The Cenozoic Era began 66 million years ago and continues to present. It is divided into Paleogene, Neogene, and Quaternary periods. Mammals diversified during this era.",
      "review_question_6": "Review question 6",
      "concept_fossil_correlation": "Concept: fossil correlation",
      "question_what_is_an_index_fossil": "Question: What is an index fossil?",
      "answer_an_index_fossil_is_a_fossil_spe": "Answer: An index fossil is a fossil species that lived during a specific, limited time period and was geographically widespread. Examples include trilobites, ammonites, and graptolites. They help correlate rocks of the same age.",
      "review_question_7": "Review question 7",
      "concept_subduction_zones": "Concept: subduction zones",
      "question_what_is_a_wadati_benioff_zone": "Question: What is a Wadati-Benioff zone?",
      "answer_a_wadati_benioff_zone_is_the_in": "Answer: A Wadati-Benioff zone is the inclined plane of earthquakes that marks a subducting slab. Earthquakes occur as the slab bends, cracks, and undergoes phase changes. Some Wadati-Benioff zones extend to 700 km depth.",
      "review_question_8": "Review question 8",
      "concept_mid_ocean_ridges": "Concept: mid-ocean ridges",
      "question_what_is_the_east_pacific_rise": "Question: What is the East Pacific Rise?",
      "answer_the_east_pacific_rise_is_the_fa": "Answer: The East Pacific Rise is the fastest-spreading mid-ocean ridge on Earth, with rates up to 16 cm/yr. It is the divergent boundary between the Pacific and Nazca plates.",
      "review_question_9": "Review question 9",
      "concept_hotspots": "Concept: hotspots",
      "question_what_is_the_hawaiian_emperor_": "Question: What is the Hawaiian-Emperor chain?",
      "answer_the_hawaiian_emperor_seamount_c": "Answer: The Hawaiian-Emperor seamount chain is a 6000 km volcanic chain that records 80 million years of Pacific Plate motion over the Hawaiian hotspot. The bend at 47 Ma marks a change in Pacific Plate motion direction.",
      "review_question_10": "Review question 10",
      "concept_transform_faults": "Concept: transform faults",
      "question_what_is_the_san_andreas_fault": "Question: What is the San Andreas Fault?",
      "answer_the_san_andreas_fault_is_a_tran": "Answer: The San Andreas Fault is a transform plate boundary between the Pacific and North American plates. It is right-lateral strike-slip. The 1906 San Francisco quake (M7.9) was on this fault.",
      "review_question_11": "Review question 11",
      "concept_plate_boundaries_2": "Concept: plate boundaries",
      "question_what_is_a_divergent_boundary_2": "Question: What is a divergent boundary?",
      "answer_a_divergent_plate_boundary_is_w_2": "Answer: A divergent plate boundary is where two plates are moving away from each other, often forming a mid-ocean ridge or continental rift. Examples include the Mid-Atlantic Ridge and the East African Rift.",
      "review_question_12": "Review question 12",
      "concept_earthquake_magnitude_2": "Concept: earthquake magnitude",
      "question_what_is_the_richter_scale_2": "Question: What is the Richter scale?",
      "answer_the_richter_scale_was_the_origi_2": "Answer: The Richter scale was the original 1935 magnitude scale developed by Charles Richter. It is logarithmic, so M5 is 10x larger than M4. It works well for small to medium quakes but saturates above M7. Modern seismology uses moment magnitude (Mw) for large events.",
      "review_question_13": "Review question 13",
      "concept_volcanic_types_2": "Concept: volcanic types",
      "question_what_is_a_stratovolcano_2": "Question: What is a stratovolcano?",
      "answer_a_stratovolcano_is_a_steep_side_2": "Answer: A stratovolcano is a steep-sided conical volcano built from alternating layers of lava and ash. Examples include Mt Fuji, Mt St Helens, and Vesuvius. They tend to produce explosive eruptions.",
      "review_question_14": "Review question 14",
      "concept_rock_cycle_2": "Concept: rock cycle",
