      "supraspinatus_tendon_rotator_cuff": "Supraspinatus tendon (rotator cuff)",
      "the_supraspinatus_is_the_most_commonly": "The supraspinatus is the most commonly torn rotator cuff muscle. It runs under the acromion where it is susceptible to impingement and tears. Overhead work like painting increases this risk significantly.",
      "racing_heart_after_exercise": "Racing Heart After Exercise",
      "which_structure_controls_the_normal_he": "Which structure controls the normal heart rhythm?",
      "sinoatrial_sa_node": "Sinoatrial (SA) node",
      "the_sa_node_in_the_right_atrium_is_the": "The SA node in the right atrium is the heart's natural pacemaker. During intense exercise, adrenaline can cause benign palpitations as the heart rate adjusts. Persistent arrhythmias should be evaluated to rule out structural heart disease.",
      "the_numb_hand": "The Numb Hand",
      "which_nerve_is_being_compressed": "Which nerve is being compressed?",
      "median_nerve_carpal_tunnel_syndrome": "Median nerve (carpal tunnel syndrome)",
      "carpal_tunnel_syndrome_is_compression_": "Carpal tunnel syndrome is compression of the median nerve under the flexor retinaculum at the wrist. The median nerve supplies sensation to the thumb and first 3.5 fingers. Repetitive wrist use is a major risk factor.",
      "the_swollen_neck_node": "The Swollen Neck Node",
      "what_diagnosis_must_be_urgently_ruled_": "What diagnosis must be urgently ruled out?",
      "lymphoma_hodgkin_lymphoma": "Lymphoma (Hodgkin lymphoma)",
      "painless_lymphadenopathy_with_b_sympto": "Painless lymphadenopathy with B-symptoms (night sweats, weight loss, fever) is the classic presentation of Hodgkin lymphoma in young adults. Biopsy showing Reed-Sternberg cells confirms the diagnosis.",
      "the_diabetic_emergency": "The Diabetic Emergency",
      "which_cells_failed_and_what_is_the_eme": "Which cells failed, and what is the emergency condition?",
      "beta_cells_of_islets_of_langerhans_dia": "Beta cells of islets of Langerhans; Diabetic Ketoacidosis (DKA)",
      "without_insulin_from_beta_cells_glucos": "Without insulin from beta cells, glucose cannot enter cells. The body burns fat, producing ketones that acidify the blood. Kussmaul breathing compensates by exhaling CO2. Treatment: IV fluids, insulin drip, and electrolyte replacement.",
      "the_broken_collarbone": "The Broken Collarbone",
      "why_is_the_middle_third_of_the_clavicl": "Why is the middle third of the clavicle the most common fracture site?",
      "the_middle_third_is_thinnest_and_has_n": "The middle third is thinnest and has no muscular reinforcement",
      "the_clavicle_is_the_most_frequently_fr": "The clavicle is the most frequently fractured bone. Its middle third is thinnest and lacks muscular protection. Force from a fall on an outstretched hand concentrates at this weak point. Most heal with sling immobilization.",
      "breathless_at_high_altitude": "Breathless at High Altitude",
      "why_does_altitude_cause_these_symptoms": "Why does altitude cause these symptoms, and which structure is most stressed?",
      "the_alveoli_and_respiratory_muscles_re": "The alveoli and respiratory muscles; reduced atmospheric oxygen causes hypoxia",
      "at_high_altitude_atmospheric_pressure_": "At high altitude, atmospheric pressure drops, reducing the partial pressure of oxygen. Less oxygen crosses the alveolar membrane. The body compensates by breathing faster and deeper, increasing respiratory muscle work.",
