      "a_squid_walks_into_a_bar_bartender_say": "A squid walks into a bar. Bartender says \"Why the long mantle?\"",
      "i_have_3_hearts_blue_blood_and_can_fit": "I have 3 hearts, blue blood, and can fit through any hole bigger than my beak. What am I?",
      "i_m_a_cephalopod_with_a_shell_on_the_o": "I'm a cephalopod with a shell on the outside. I'm a \"living fossil.\" What am I?",
      "i_impersonate_other_animals_to_confuse": "I impersonate other animals to confuse predators. Sometimes I'm a flatfish, sometimes a sea snake. What am I?",
      "dear_families_this_week_we_re_starting": "Dear families,\n\nThis week we're starting a 2-week unit on cephalopods — octopuses, squids, cuttlefish, and nautiluses. These animals are among the most fascinating biology subjects available to students, and they raise important questions about evolution, cognition, ecology, and ethics.\n\nWhat your child will be learning:\n\n• How cephalopods change color almost instantly using specialized skin cells\n• Why octopuses are considered one of the most intelligent invertebrates\n• How cephalopod populations are responding to climate change\n• Whether (and how) we should farm or eat octopuses given their likely sentience\n\nWe'll be using a free educational simulator (Cephalopod Lab) which is web-based, requires no special accounts, and stores no personal data. Students can access it from home if they want to continue learning. We may also watch a clip from \"My Octopus Teacher\" — please reach out if you have any concerns.\n\nThings you can do at home to support learning:\n\n• Read Sy Montgomery's \"The Soul of an Octopus\" (chapter highlights are great)\n• Visit a local aquarium if you can\n• Watch BBC Earth's octopus camouflage videos on YouTube\n• Have your child show you the simulator + explain what they've learned\n• Talk about cephalopod welfare at dinner (if your family eats octopus or squid)\n\nQuestions? Please reach out anytime.\n\nThank you,\n[Teacher signature]",
      "dear_families_we_ve_completed_week_1_o": "Dear families,\n\nWe've completed Week 1 of our cephalopod biology unit. Students have:\n\n• Learned the chromatophore mechanism for color change\n• Designed cognition tests for octopuses\n• Studied the optic gland (the organ that causes octopus mothers to die after laying eggs)\n• Begun building food webs showing cephalopod ecology\n\nNext week we'll cover:\n\n• Cephalopod evolution (500 million years)\n• Sentience + welfare ethics\n• Climate change impacts\n• Final capstone projects\n\nThis week's wins:\n\n• Several students wrote excellent essays on cephalopod intelligence\n• Class debate on octopus farming was substantive + respectful\n• Multiple students have signed up for iNaturalist accounts for citizen science\n\nThis week's questions for dinner-table conversation:\n\n• How do you know if an animal is conscious?\n• Should we change how we treat animals when we learn they're likely sentient?\n• Why do octopuses live such short lives, and what trade-off does that represent evolutionarily?\n\nQuestions? Reach out anytime.\n\nThank you,\n[Teacher signature]",
      "dear_families_we_ve_completed_our_2_we": "Dear families,\n\nWe've completed our 2-week cephalopod biology unit. Your child:\n\n• Developed scientific reasoning skills\n• Used evidence to support claims about controversial topics\n• Engaged with primary scientific literature\n• Completed a capstone project of their own design\n\nFor students who want to keep learning:\n\n• Read \"Other Minds\" by Peter Godfrey-Smith (HS+ level)\n• Read \"The Soul of an Octopus\" by Sy Montgomery (MS+ level)\n• Watch the MBARI YouTube channel for deep-sea cephalopod content\n• Continue contributing observations to iNaturalist\n• Explore the simulator further — we only used about a third of its content\n\nFor students who want to take this further:\n\n• Apply to local marine biology summer programs\n• Explore science fair projects (we have a Project Ideas tab in the simulator)\n• Contact local university marine biology labs about volunteer opportunities\n• Consider career paths in marine biology (we have a Careers tab too)\n\nThank you for supporting your child's science learning. Cephalopod biology is one of the richest gateways into thinking about ecology, evolution, cognition, and ethics — and it's clear our students have engaged seriously with all of these.\n\nQuestions? Reach out anytime.\n\nThank you,\n[Teacher signature]",
      "the_squid_giant_axon_papers": "The squid giant axon papers",
      "in_a_series_of_5_papers_published_in_j": "In a series of 5 papers published in J. Physiol., Hodgkin + Huxley used the SQUID GIANT AXON to map the action potential — the fundamental electrical signal of all nervous systems.",
      "the_neural_anatomy_of_octopus_vulgaris": "The neural anatomy of Octopus vulgaris",
      "in_his_1971_book_the_anatomy_of_the_ne": "In his 1971 book \"The Anatomy of the Nervous System of Octopus vulgaris,\" Young presented a comprehensive map of the octopus brain — ~38 distinct lobes, each with specific functions.",
      "the_optic_gland_senescence_experiment": "The optic gland senescence experiment",
      "wodinsky_performed_a_landmark_experime": "Wodinsky performed a landmark experiment showing that the optic gland controls brooding + senescence in female octopuses.",
      "observational_learning_in_octopus": "Observational learning in octopus",
      "fiorito_scotto_demonstrated_that_octop": "Fiorito + Scotto demonstrated that octopuses can learn a task by WATCHING another octopus do it — a cognitive ability previously documented only in vertebrates + some primates.",
      "dynamic_mimicry_in_the_mimic_octopus": "Dynamic mimicry in the mimic octopus",
      "this_indo_pacific_octopus_species_was_": "This Indo-Pacific octopus species was newly described in 1998. Norman et al. documented its remarkable flexibility — impersonating different species depending on which predator was present.",
      "coconut_octopus_tool_use": "Coconut octopus tool use",
