      "why_do_you_think_octopuses_can_change_": "Why do you think octopuses can change color so quickly?",
      "good_observation_that_change_is_rapid_": "Good observation that change is rapid + that camouflage is for protection. Used the term \"chromatophores\" correctly. Could be improved by: (a) naming a specific source from the in-canvas info, (b) extending to consider what camouflage cannot do (e.g., against sharks).",
      "why_do_you_think_octopuses_can_change__2": "Why do you think octopuses can change color so quickly?",
      "strong_response_uses_correct_technical": "Strong response — uses correct technical vocabulary (chromatophore, opsin), gives a specific number (200 ms), connects to biology (predator pressure), and acknowledges an open question (how does a color-blind animal match color?). Could improve by citing the specific researcher (Mäthger 2010 documented skin opsins).",
      "explain_why_octopus_camouflage_is_an_e": "Explain why octopus camouflage is an evolutionary adaptation.",
      "good_integration_of_mechanism_chromato": "Good integration of mechanism (chromatophore biology) with evolutionary process (natural selection). Identifies a limitation of camouflage — shows scientific maturity. Could improve by: (a) specifying which trait variation natural selection acts on, (b) discussing the energy cost of running the camouflage system.",
      "cephalopods_vertebrates_evolved_simila": "Cephalopods + vertebrates evolved similar eye structures independently. Explain this as a convergent evolution case study.",
      "excellent_identifies_convergent_evolut": "Excellent. Identifies convergent evolution clearly, gives multiple specific shared + distinguishing features, cites peer-reviewed literature (Tomarev & Piatigorsky), and connects to broader evolutionary biology questions. The connection to \"anti-intelligent-design\" is a strong synthesis — shows that the student is connecting NGSS standards to actual scientific arguments. Word choice is precise + technically accurate.",
      "evaluate_the_evidence_for_cephalopod_s": "Evaluate the evidence for cephalopod sentience and discuss the policy implications.",
      "excellent_synthesis_of_scientific_evid": "Excellent synthesis of scientific evidence, policy analysis, and ethical reasoning. Multiple peer-reviewed citations from recent literature. Strong claims supported by evidence. Discusses cultural complexity without dismissing it. This response could be the basis for an AP Capstone individual research paper. Suggested next steps: develop into a 4,000-word position paper; submit to a high school journal or essay competition.",
      "print_or_pull_up_a_photo_of_an_octopus": "Print or pull up a photo of an octopus. Have your child draw it. Then ask: \"What did you notice that I didn't mention?\" — kids often notice details (suckers, color spots, eye shape) that adults gloss over.",
      "make_cards_with_octopus_on_one_side_th": "Make cards with octopus on one side + their prey (crab, fish, clam) on the other. Or paint rocks to look like crabs + hide them in your yard. Have kids find them.",
      "visit_a_local_tide_pool_30_minutes_bef": "Visit a local tide pool 30 minutes before LOW tide. Look in deep pools for small octopuses, crabs, anemones. Take pictures (don't move animals).",
      "visit_local_aquarium_pick_one_cephalop": "Visit local aquarium. Pick ONE cephalopod (if available) and observe for 20 minutes. Every 30 seconds, write down what it's doing.",
      "look_around_your_house_pick_three_diff": "Look around your house. Pick three different surfaces (couch, wood floor, bookshelf). For each, imagine an octopus settled there + draw the camouflage colors + pattern they would need.",
      "if_your_family_eats_cephalopods_discus": "IF your family eats cephalopods, discuss together: How was this animal sourced? Are we comfortable with current welfare standards? What questions could we ask the restaurant or fisher?",
      "watch_together_afterward_did_the_docum": "Watch together. Afterward: Did the documentary affect how you think about octopuses? Is the relationship Foster shows accurate science or anthropomorphism? Should we change how we treat animals based on this?",
      "walk_a_beach_or_coastal_area_use_inatu": "Walk a beach or coastal area. Use iNaturalist to identify anything you see. If you see a cephalopod, photograph + tag. Submit observations to the citizen-science database.",
      "visit_aquarium_critique_their_cephalop": "Visit aquarium. Critique their cephalopod displays using EU 2010/63 welfare guidelines (printable from the In Sim → Educator tab). What's good, what could improve, what would you ask the curator?",
      "following_major_opposition_from_compas": "Following major opposition from Compassion in World Farming, Eurogroup for Animals, and multiple cephalopod biologists, Spain has paused approval of the Nueva Pescanova octopus farm pending new welfare guidelines.",
      "new_high_speed_imaging_neural_recordin": "New high-speed imaging + neural recording resolved how octopus arms coordinate without central control — a \"stiffening wave\" of muscle contraction propagates down the arm.",
      "a_previously_unknown_octopus_species_e": "A previously unknown octopus species — Eledonella verbruggeni — was described from MBARI expedition footage. Adds to the ongoing discovery of deep-sea cephalopod diversity.",
      "new_research_published_in_nature_docum": "New research published in Nature documented REM-like sleep states in Octopus laqueus, supporting the hypothesis that cephalopods experience dreams.",
      "following_the_birch_et_al_2021_lse_rep": "Following the Birch et al. 2021 LSE Report, the UK formally added cephalopods + decapods to the sentience list under the Animal Welfare (Sentience) Act 2022.",
