      "my_octopus_teacher_octopus": "\"My Octopus Teacher\" octopus",
      "chromatophore": "Chromatophore",
      "a_pigment_containing_cell_surrounded_b": "A pigment-containing cell surrounded by 15-25 radial muscle fibers that, when contracted simultaneously, stretch the pigment sac to up to 15x its resting diameter.",
      "iridophore": "Iridophore",
      "a_non_pigmented_cell_containing_stacks": "A non-pigmented cell containing stacks of thin reflective platelets made of the protein reflectin. Color comes from interference patterns in the platelet stack.",
      "leucophore": "Leucophore",
      "a_non_pigmented_white_scattering_cell_": "A non-pigmented white-scattering cell. Reflects ambient light broadband to give white reference patches in skin.",
      "dermal_papilla": "Dermal papilla",
      "a_3d_protrusion_of_the_skin_controlled": "A 3D protrusion of the skin, controlled by a ring-of-muscle network underneath. Allows cephalopods to make their skin TEXTURE match the substrate, not just color.",
      "photophore_light_organ": "Photophore (light organ)",
      "a_specialized_light_producing_organ_in": "A specialized light-producing organ. Intrinsic photophores (e.g., firefly squid) contain the cephalopod's own luciferin + luciferase enzymes. Symbiotic photophores (e.g., bobtail squid) house bioluminescent bacteria.",
      "carbonate_caves_in_coastal_limestone_r": "Carbonate caves in coastal limestone reefs; lava-tube caves in volcanic islands; submerged stalactite caves. Permanent darkness inside; reduced water flow; specialized fauna.",
      "a_subtidal_habitat_dominated_by_large_": "A subtidal habitat dominated by large brown algae (Macrocystis, Nereocystis, Laminaria). Canopy reaches up to 60 m above the sea floor; understory grades from kelp blades to seafloor.",
      "cracks_in_spreading_ridge_basalt_where": "Cracks in spreading-ridge basalt where superheated (up to 400°C) mineralized water jets out. Supports a CHEMOSYNTHESIS-based ecosystem — life without sunlight, fueled by H₂S oxidation by chemosynthetic bacteria.",
      "underwater_mountain_rising_at_least_10": "Underwater mountain rising at least 1000 m above the surrounding sea floor without reaching the surface. Steep slopes create localized currents that aggregate plankton + larvae.",
      "the_zone_exposed_at_low_tide_submerged": "The zone exposed at low tide + submerged at high tide. Subject to extreme daily variation in temperature, salinity, oxygen, and predator pressure.",
      "tropical_coastal_trees_that_grow_in_sa": "Tropical coastal trees that grow in salt water. Their prop roots create complex underwater habitat at the land-sea interface.",
      "mid_water_layers_typically_200_1000_m_": "Mid-water layers (typically 200-1000 m depth) where oxygen concentrations drop below ~20 μM. Found globally; expanding under climate change.",
      "the_most_studied_octopus_in_science_fo": "The most-studied octopus in science. Found in temperate + subtropical waters worldwide. The model organism for cephalopod neurobiology, behavior, and intelligence research.",
      "tiny_beautiful_and_one_of_the_most_ven": "Tiny, beautiful, and one of the most venomous animals on Earth. Four named species — H. lunulata, H. maculosa, H. fasciata, H. nierstraszi — all share the iconic blue ring display when threatened.",
      "discovered_only_in_1998_off_sulawesi_i": "Discovered only in 1998 off Sulawesi, Indonesia. Famous for flexibly impersonating other species — sea snakes, lionfish, flatfish, jellyfish — during a single dive depending on predator type.",
      "the_most_studied_cephalopod_for_visual": "The most-studied cephalopod for visual perception + display behavior. The \"intense zebra\" display research has been foundational for understanding how cephalopod skin functions as a communication channel.",
      "the_world_s_largest_octopus_arm_span_o": "The world's largest octopus — arm-span over 7 m + body mass over 50 kg have been documented. Lives along the cold Pacific coast from California to Japan. Heavily studied due to its size + tractability in captivity.",
      "deep_sea_cirrate_octopuses_the_deepest": "Deep-sea cirrate octopuses — the deepest octopus genus. Their two ear-like fins flap continuously to swim. Translucent body. Almost no chromatophores (no sun = no need for camouflage).",
      "not_a_true_squid_or_octopus_a_living_f": "Not a true squid or octopus — a \"living fossil\" representing an entire separate cephalopod lineage. Lives in oxygen-minimum zones (200-1000 m). Eats marine snow with sticky filaments — unique among cephalopods. Doesn't use ink.",
      "a_3_5_cm_tropical_squid_with_the_most_": "A 3-5 cm tropical squid with the most-studied animal-bacterial mutualism in biology. Their light organ houses Vibrio fischeri bacteria that glow on demand to camouflage the squid against moonlight from below. The squid-Vibrio system is the textbook model for ALL host-microbiome biology — including human gut microbiome research.",
      "the_only_living_cephalopod_with_an_ext": "The only living cephalopod with an external shell — a \"living fossil.\" Lineage has changed little in 500 million years. Lives in deep water (typically 200-500 m). The genus is now CITES-listed (2017) due to shell trade.",
      "pelagic_predator_of_the_eastern_pacifi": "Pelagic predator of the Eastern Pacific. Up to 2 m mantle length, ~50 kg. Hunts in schools of 20-1200 individuals. Aggressive — Mexican fishermen call them diablos rojos. Skin chromatophores flash red/white at 2-4 Hz when hunting.",
      "caribbean_reef_dwelling_diurnal_octopu": "Caribbean reef-dwelling diurnal octopus. Distinctive blue-green iridescence + dramatic chromatophore displays during mating. Used in cognition research at multiple Caribbean stations.",
      "famous_for_carrying_coconut_halves_acr_2": "Famous for carrying coconut halves across the sea floor. The first documented case of tool use in an invertebrate involving DELAYED object manipulation. Walks BIPEDALLY on its two back arms while carrying coconuts (Huffard et al. 2005, Science).",
      "cites_convention_on_international_trad": "CITES (Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species)",
      "eu_directive_2010_63_eu": "EU Directive 2010/63/EU",
      "uk_animal_welfare_sentience_act_2022": "UK Animal Welfare (Sentience) Act 2022",
