      "no_way_too_fast_for_biological_propuls": "No — way too fast for biological propulsion underwater.",
      "in_ngss_engaging_in_argument_from_evid": "In NGSS, \"engaging in argument from evidence\" requires students to:",
      "memorize_facts": "Memorize facts",
      "no_that_s_the_old_style_of_science_tea": "No — that's the OLD style of science teaching, not NGSS.",
      "make_claims_support_them_with_data_obs": "Make claims, support them with data/observations, and respond to counterclaims",
      "correct_practice_7_is_a_core_argumenta": "Correct. Practice 7 is a core argumentation practice — claim + evidence + reasoning, plus counterclaim engagement.",
      "only_listen_to_the_teacher_s_explanati": "Only listen to the teacher's explanation",
      "do_calculations_only": "Do calculations only",
      "no_math_is_one_part_but_argumentation_": "No — math is one PART, but argumentation is broader.",
      "is_there_scientific_evidence_of_play_b": "Is there scientific evidence of PLAY behavior in octopuses?",
      "no_invertebrates_don_t_play": "No — invertebrates don't play",
      "no_mather_anderson_1999_provided_the_f": "No — Mather & Anderson (1999) provided the first documented evidence of octopus play.",
      "yes_they_repeat_non_functional_behavio": "Yes — they repeat non-functional behaviors with floating objects",
      "correct_two_specimens_at_the_seattle_a": "Correct. Two specimens at the Seattle Aquarium repeatedly released + grabbed a floating pill bottle in a tank current — a behavior pattern that meets the criteria for animal play (Mather & Anderson 1999, J. Comp. Psychol.).",
      "only_juvenile_octopuses": "Only juvenile octopuses",
      "no_the_documented_examples_were_adult": "No — the documented examples were adult.",
      "yes_but_only_in_lab_settings": "Yes, but only in lab settings",
      "aquarium_setting_but_the_behavior_is_i": "Aquarium setting, but the behavior is interpreted as genuine play.",
      "about_how_many_living_cephalopod_speci": "About how many living cephalopod species are known?",
      "way_too_low_2": "Way too low.",
      "correct_800_living_species_are_describ": "Correct. ~800 living species are described, but the true number is likely higher — deep-sea species are still being discovered, and several \"species complexes\" are being split into multiple species via genetic analysis.",
      "too_many": "Too many.",
      "way_too_many": "Way too many.",
      "what_is_the_taxonomic_class_that_conta": "What is the taxonomic CLASS that contains all octopuses, squids, cuttlefish, and nautiluses?",
      "mollusca_2": "Mollusca",
      "no_that_s_the_phylum_larger_group_also": "No — that's the PHYLUM (larger group; also includes snails, clams, etc.).",
      "cephalopoda_2": "Cephalopoda",
      "correct_cephalopoda_is_the_class_withi": "Correct. Cephalopoda is the class within phylum Mollusca that contains all cephalopods. The name means \"head-foot\" in Greek.",
      "coleoidea_2": "Coleoidea",
      "that_s_a_subclass_only_cephalopods_wit": "That's a SUBCLASS — only cephalopods without external shells.",
      "octopodiformes": "Octopodiformes",
      "that_s_a_more_specific_order_just_octo": "That's a more specific ORDER, just octopuses + vampire squid.",
      "plankton_bloom": "Plankton Bloom",
      "plankton_blooms_occur_when_nutrients_o": "Plankton blooms occur when nutrients (often from upwelling or runoff) spike. They feed the entire pelagic food web — phytoplankton → krill → small fish → cephalopods → top predators. Massive blooms can become harmful (HABs) when toxic dinoflagellates dominate.",
      "bait_ball": "Bait Ball",
      "a_bait_ball_is_an_emergent_defense_whe": "A bait ball is an emergent defense: when small fish detect predators, they pack into a sphere that maximizes packing density. This makes individual fish harder to target — but signals \"free food\" to every predator in the area, including dolphins, sharks, sailfish, and squid.",
      "surface_storm": "Surface Storm",
      "storms_mix_the_surface_layer_down_to_1": "Storms mix the surface layer down to 10-30 m depth, suspending sediment + delivering nutrients to the photic zone. Many octopuses retreat to dens during storms; cuttlefish and squid often move to deeper water until conditions stabilize.",
      "cold_upwelling": "Cold Upwelling",
      "coastal_upwelling_driven_by_wind_ekman": "Coastal upwelling — driven by wind + Ekman transport — is responsible for ~5% of global ocean primary production. Major upwelling zones (Humboldt Current, Benguela Current) support the world's largest fisheries. Octopuses and squid often thrive here.",
      "squid_mating_swarm": "Squid Mating Swarm",
      "market_squid_doryteuthis_opalescens_fo": "Market squid (Doryteuthis opalescens) form massive mating aggregations off Monterey Bay every spring — sometimes 100+ million individuals — over 1-2 weeks. The display features elaborate stripe + dot patterns flashing on chromatophores at 2-4 Hz.",
      "jellyfish_bloom": "Jellyfish Bloom",
      "jellyfish_blooms_have_become_more_freq": "Jellyfish blooms have become more frequent globally since 1990 — driven by warming water + overfishing of jellyfish predators + eutrophication. Some scientists call this the \"rise of slime\" trend in marine ecosystems.",
      "distant_whale_song": "Distant Whale Song",
      "sperm_whales_hunt_squid_using_powerful": "Sperm whales hunt squid using powerful echolocation clicks up to 230 dB. They can dive over 2000 m and stay submerged for up to 90 minutes. A single whale eats 700+ squid per day.",
      "cleaning_station": "Cleaning Station",
      "cleaner_shrimp_and_cleaner_wrasses_pic": "Cleaner shrimp and cleaner wrasses pick parasites off larger fish at designated reef sites — a textbook example of mutualism. Octopuses have been observed visiting cleaning stations, though they're less frequent customers than fish.",
      "coral_spawning": "Coral Spawning",
      "in_the_great_barrier_reef_130_coral_sp": "In the Great Barrier Reef, ~130 coral species spawn synchronously over 2-3 nights each November. They release gametes en masse on the same lunar cue — a strategy called \"predator satiation\" that protects most gametes by overwhelming predator capacity.",
      "tagged_shark_survey": "Tagged Shark Survey",
      "satellite_tagged_sharks_have_revolutio": "Satellite-tagged sharks have revolutionized marine ecology — we now know reef shark home ranges, migration corridors, and depth use in real time. Many shark-tagging programs are citizen-science accessible (OCEARCH, etc.).",
      "mystery_wreckage": "Mystery Wreckage",
      "marine_debris_falls_to_the_sea_floor_c": "Marine debris falls to the sea floor continuously. Octopuses readily adopt human-made objects as shelter — Freitas et al. 2022 found 75% of wild O. vulgaris in their Brazilian survey used anthropogenic shelters. This is both opportunistic + a marker of pollution.",
      "dolphin_pod": "Dolphin Pod",
      "bottlenose_dolphins_have_been_document_2": "Bottlenose dolphins have been documented chasing octopuses — and learning to bash them against the seafloor to subdue them before eating. The behavior is socially transmitted within pods.",
      "cephalopod_cognition_2": "Cephalopod Cognition",
