      "most_marine_populations_are_declining": "Most marine populations are declining. ",
      "cephalopods_are_not": "Cephalopods are not",
      "global_cephalopod_biomass_has_been_cli": " — global cephalopod biomass has been climbing for decades. A 2016 paper (Doubleday et al., ",
      "current_biology": "Current Biology",
      "analyzed_50_years_of_fishery_ecosystem": ") analyzed 50+ years of fishery + ecosystem data across 35 species and found a consistent upward trend.",
      "why_several_theories_1": "Why? Several theories: (1) ",
      "short_lifespan_rapid_reproduction": "short lifespan + rapid reproduction",
      "lets_cephalopods_respond_quickly_to_ch": " lets cephalopods respond quickly to changing conditions; (2) ",
      "release_from_fish_competition_predatio": "release from fish competition + predation",
      "their_main_competitors_are_being_fishe": " (their main competitors are being fished out); (3) ",
      "warming_oceans_favor_cephalopod_metabo": "warming oceans favor cephalopod metabolism",
      "they_grow_faster_in_warmer_water_4": " — they grow faster in warmer water; (4) ",
      "dietary_flexibility": "dietary flexibility",
      "most_cephalopods_are_opportunistic_car": " — most cephalopods are opportunistic carnivores that can switch prey easily.",
      "the_flip_side_targeted_fisheries_are_e": "The flip side: targeted fisheries are expanding to match the population increase. Global cephalopod catch is now ",
      "4_million_tons_year": "~4 million tons/year",
      "nearly_all_of_it_consumed_by_humans_wi": " — nearly all of it consumed by humans. Within that, squid dominate (~3M tons), then octopus + cuttlefish. China, Japan, South Korea, Peru, and several Mediterranean fisheries are the largest players.",
      "iucn_status_by_species": "📋 IUCN status by species",
      "the_global_cephalopod_fishery": "🎣 The global cephalopod fishery",
      "4_million_tons_of_cephalopods_are_caug": "~4 million tons of cephalopods are caught globally each year. Squid dominate the catch (~3M tons), followed by octopus (~400k tons) and cuttlefish (~300k tons). The fishery has tripled in the last 60 years.",
      "major_fisheries_include": "Major fisheries include:",
