      "these_are_the_minimum_internal_tempera": "These are the minimum internal temperatures. A meat thermometer is the only way to know for sure. Color is unreliable — pink chicken at 165°F is safe; brown chicken at 140°F is not.",
      "pitfall": "⚠️ Pitfall: ",
      "cross_contamination_rules": "🚫 Cross-Contamination Rules",
      "pathogens_move_from_raw_meat_hands_cut": "Pathogens move from raw meat → hands → cutting board → ready-to-eat food. The fixes are simple but easy to forget mid-cook.",
      "red_board_for_raw_meat_green_for_produ": "Red board for raw meat, green for produce. Many home kitchens skip this — it's the #1 home-kitchen cross-contamination source.",
      "20_seconds_with_soap_hot_water_the_20_": "20 seconds with soap + hot water. The 20 seconds is what dislodges the bacteria — soap alone doesn't.",
      "surface_thaws_fast_bacteria_multiply_o": "Surface thaws fast → bacteria multiply on the outside while inside is still frozen. Fridge keeps the whole thing under 40°F.",
      "marinade_that_touched_raw_meat_contain": "Marinade that touched raw meat contains those pathogens. Boil it 1 min before using as a finishing sauce, or make extra separately.",
      "damp_kitchen_sponges_harbor_more_bacte": "Damp kitchen sponges harbor more bacteria per square cm than the toilet seat. Microwaving wet for 90 seconds sanitizes most of it.",
      "cooked_food_in_danger_zone_40_140_f_in": "Cooked food in danger zone (40-140°F) → into fridge within 2 hours (1 hour if room is 90°F+).",
      "the_top_9_allergens_fda_faster_act": "⚠️ The Top 9 Allergens (FDA + FASTER Act)",
      "these_9_cause_90_of_all_severe_food_al": "These 9 cause ~90% of all severe food allergic reactions in the US. Sesame was added in 2023. By law, packaged food must declare these. The \"hidden in\" column matters most — that's where surprises happen.",
      "hidden_in": "🕵️ Hidden in: ",
      "20_second_handwash_cdc_who": "🧼 20-Second Handwash (CDC + WHO)",
      "soap_20_seconds_friction_the_minimum_f": "Soap + 20 seconds + friction = the minimum for hand sanitation in a kitchen. The mechanical action (friction) is what dislodges bacteria — soap loosens them, water rinses them away.",
      "pick_a_cut_to_learn": "Pick a cut to learn",
      "why_uniformity_matters": "🎯 Why Uniformity Matters",
      "when_pieces_are_different_sizes_they_f": "When pieces are different sizes, they finish cooking at different times. Small pieces burn while large pieces are still raw. Uniform cuts = uniform cook = no kitchen guessing.",
      "uneven_cuts": "❌ Uneven cuts",
      "small_pieces_blacken_at_6_min_while_la": "Small pieces blacken at 6 min while large pieces are still raw inside at 12 min. You either eat charcoal + crunchy, or you cook so long the small pieces are inedible.",
      "uniform_cuts": "✅ Uniform cuts",
      "every_piece_reaches_doneness_at_the_sa": "Every piece reaches doneness at the same moment. You can leave the pan and trust the clock. This is why professional kitchens drill knife skills before anything else.",
      "the_claw_grip_finger_safety": "✋ The Claw Grip (Finger Safety)",
      "curl_your_guiding_fingers_inward_so_yo": "Curl your guiding fingers INWARD so your knuckles face the blade, not your fingertips. The flat of the blade slides along your knuckles as a guide. If the knife slips, it slides up your knuckle wall — not into your fingertip.",
